      "title": "On integral representation of the Drazin inverse in Banach algebra",
      "abstract": "where u \u2208 A is quasinilpotent, that is, limn\u2192\u221e \u2016un\u20161/n = 0 [4, Definition 4.1]. (See also [3].) This definition subsumes (for Banach algebras) the pseudo-inverse defined originally for elements of semigroups and rings [2], which arises when u is nilpotent. The Drazin inverse b of a is unique when it exists, and is denoted by aD. The Drazin index i(a) of a is defined to be 0 if a is invertible, k if the element u in (1.1) is nilpotent of order k, and \u221e otherwise. According to [4], an element a \u2208 A is Drazin invertible if and only if 0 is not an accumulation point of \u03c3(a). This occurs if and only if there exists an idempotent p \u2208 A such that"
